04013nam a22005655i 9780231537919DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20142014nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2014003432  a(OCoLC)984649197  a97802315379197 a10.7312/riti168682doi  a(DE-B1597)458480  a(OCoLC)890676063  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aE169.12b.R538 2014 4aE169.12b.R538 2014 7aPHI0190002bisacsh04a320.973090492231 aRitivoi, Andreea, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIntimate Strangers :bArendt, Marcuse, Solzhenitsyn, and Said in American Political Discourse /cAndreea Ritivoi.  aPilot project. eBook available to selected US libraries only 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (320 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tINTRODUCTION -- t1. THE STRANGER PERSONA -- t2. HANNAH ARENDT: THE THINKER AND THE AMERICAN REPUBLIC -- t3. HERBERT MARCUSE’S GERMAN REVOLUTION IN AMERICA -- t4. COLD WAR PROPHESIES: ALEXANDER SOLZHENITSYN AND MYTHOLOGICAL AMERICA -- t5. EDWARD SAID AND THE CLASH OF IDENTITIES -- tCONCLUSION -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHannah Arendt, Herbert Marcuse, Alexander Solzhenitsyn, and Edward Said each steered major intellectual and political schools of thought in American political discourse after World War II, yet none of them was American, which proved crucial to their ways of arguing and reasoning both in and out of the American context. In an effort to convince their audiences they were American enough, these thinkers deployed deft rhetorical strategies that made their cosmopolitanism feel acceptable, inspiring radical new approaches to longstanding problems in American politics. Speaking like natives, they also exploited their foreignness to entice listeners to embrace alternative modes of thought. Intimate Strangers unpacks this "stranger ethos," a blend of detachment and involvement that manifested in the persona of a prophet for Solzhenitsyn, an impartial observer for Arendt, a mentor for Marcuse, and a victim for Said. Yet despite its many successes, the stranger ethos did alienate many audiences, and critics continue to dismiss these thinkers not for their positions but because of their foreign point of view. This book encourages readers to reject this kind of critical xenophobia, throwing support behind a political discourse that accounts for the ideals of citizens and noncitizens alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aIntellectualszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aPolitics and culturezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aRhetoricxPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066586440uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/riti1686840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231537919423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231537919.jpg  a978-3-11-066586-4  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles